  "warnings": [
    "Reference ranges are physiologically higher in populations living at high altitudes and in heavy smokers.",
    "Hematocrit may be falsely elevated in severe dehydration due to plasma volume contraction.",
    "Hematocrit may be falsely decreased in overhydration (hypervolemia).",
    "Acute blood loss may not be reflected immediately in the hematocrit due to compensatory plasma volume shifts.",
    "The hematocrit may be unreliable in patients with microcytic (e.g., iron deficiency) or macrocytic anemia.",
    "Pediatric ranges are highly age-dependent; ensure exact age is used for interpretation.",
    "Values may be slightly decreased in older adults (over age 60) due to declining erythropoiesis.",
    "Pregnancy causes physiologic hemodilution with lower hematocrit particularly in the second and third trimesters.",
    "EDTA samples stored for prolonged periods (>24 hours) may show increased hematocrit due to RBC swelling.",
    "Patient age, sex, nutritional status, and residential altitude all contribute to natural variations."
  ],
  "notes": [
    "Hematocrit can be measured directly via centrifugation (microhematocrit method) or calculated as Hct = RBC count × MCV / 10.",
    "The neonate has a high hematocrit at birth (up to 64%) which declines to a physiologic nadir around 2-3 months of age.",
    "Erythrocytosis is defined as a persistently elevated hematocrit (>0.52 in males, >0.48 in females for >2 months).",
    "When hematocrit exceeds 60% in males or 56% in females, true increase in red cell mass (rather than apparent erythrocytosis) can be assumed.",
    "JAK2 mutation testing is indicated for evaluation of suspected polycythemia vera.",
    "The hematocrit is part of the complete blood count and is also known as packed cell volume (PCV).",
    "LOINC code: 4544-3; SNOMED-CT ID: 28317006."
  ],
